Introduction¶

The bid-ask spread is a fundamental concept in financial markets, representing the difference between the highest price a buyer is willing to pay (bid) and the lowest price a seller is willing to accept (ask). This spread is crucial in market-making and liquidity provision, and its optimization helps in **maximizing dealer profits while minimizing losses to informed traders.

In this analysis, we use the Copeland & Galai model to find the optimal bid-ask spread, incorporating:

  • Liquidity traders who trade for non-informational reasons.
  • Informed traders who possess superior knowledge about future price movements.
  • Weibull distribution to model asset price behavior.

Using mathematical modeling and numerical optimization, we determine the spread that balances profit from liquidity traders and losses to informed traders.

Methodology¶

Weibull Distribution for Price Modeling¶

We assume that asset prices follow a Weibull distribution, defined as:

$$ f(S) = \frac{k}{\lambda} \left(\frac{S}{\lambda}\right)^{k-1} e^{-(S/\lambda)^k} $$

where:

  • ( \lambda ) (scale parameter) controls the price level.
  • ( k ) (shape parameter) controls price variation.

Liquidity vs. Informed Traders¶

  • Liquidity traders transact randomly, providing **profit to the dealer.
  • Informed traders trade strategically, causing **losses.

The dealer maximizes profit by choosing an optimal bid-ask spread , ensuring expected profit remains non-negative.

bid_ask.py module¶

This defines key functions for optimizing the bid-ask spread. It includes the Weibull distribution for modeling price behavior, functions for computing liquidity and informed trader probabilities, and a utility function that calculates dealer profit by balancing expected revenue from liquidity traders and expected losses to informed traders using numerical integration.

main.py¶

This script runs the full analysis and visualization of the bid-ask spread optimization. It imports functions from bid_ask.py, sets market parameters, and performs numerical optimization to find the optimal bid-ask spread using scipy.optimize.minimize(). The results include:

  • Optimal bid and ask prices based on dealer profit maximization.
  • Visualization of the Weibull distribution for asset prices.
  • Expected revenue and cost analysis to determine profitability.
  • Plotting the bid-ask spread and expected values for liquidity and informed traders.

This script provides a complete market simulation, helping analyze how bid-ask spreads adjust in different trading environments.

Conclusion¶

  • The optimal bid-ask spread was found to be {optimal_spread: 15.3}, maximizing dealer profit while balancing liquidity and informed trader risks.
  • Informed traders increase Market Maker losses, requiring a wider spread to compensate.
  • Higher liquidity participation tends to narrow the bid-ask spread, as market makers face lower risk and increased competition, which can improve market efficiency.

These results align with Copeland & Galai's theoretical framework, showing how market makers strategically set spreads to optimize profit in financial markets.
